      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot. Garden ¶ 15 Oct. 58. ¶ My dear Dr Hooker. ¶  ¶ By the accident, which happened to the mail, your letter ¶  was delayed a month over the due time &amp; I could therefore not respond to it ea...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">58.10.15</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 44a.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot. Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">15 Oct. 58.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Dr Hooker.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>By the accident, which happened to the mail, your letter<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker to M, 22 June 1858?</p>
               </note> was delayed a month over the due time &amp; I could therefore not respond to it earlier. I wished to express to you to your worthy father many thanks for all kindness evinced. Just after the bustle of our spring show of the Hort Society is over I have time yet to write a few words before the mail closes. A few days ago I got through my bookseller (not Mr Pamplin, who is far behind his enterprising colonial colleagues) the 6. fasc of F. Tasm.,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1860); fascicle 6, the first of vol. 2, was published on 3 May 1858 (TL2).</p>
               </note> which is certainly a valuable continuation of a great work in a national series. Mr Archers aid in settling the [limits] of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> &amp; above all his splendid drawings (altho I have only seen the block copy) are highly creditable, altho' my own views assign other limits to the species. Thus for instance I think your whole group including the <name key="Caladenia%20Patersonia">Caladenia Patersonia</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. patersonii</seg>?</p>
               </note> is comprehended under my <name key="Caladenia%20pulcherrima">Caladenia pulcherrima</name>; again evidently you are at variance with Prof Lindley in some of the <name key="Diuris">Diuris</name>
               <name key="Pterostylis">Pterostylis</name> &amp; <name key="Thelymitra">Thelymitra</name>s &amp;c according to his paper on my first South Austr &amp; Tasm. orchids in the Linnaea.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Lindley (1853).</p>
               </note> — My fourth No of Fragmenta, which with the 4th No of pharm journal is sent incomplete to day in the official mail, will bring several very interesting additions to your 6th fasc of Fl. Tasm.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The fourth part of the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Fragmenta</seg> consisting of four gatherings was not published until February 1859 (B59.02.03). <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Dendrobium milligani</seg>, the only Tasmanian plant described in that fascicle, is in the third gathering, p. 88. B58.10.02 does not discuss Tasmanian plants in particular.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I do not think that <name key="Hypoxis%20pusilla">Hypoxis pusilla</name> is more than a diminutive altered state of H. glabella formed in dry locality. If the pedicellate var of Trig.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Triglochin</seg>.</p>
               </note> centrocarpum is identical with the Swan Riv. plant, Then T. trichophorum must be added as a synonym.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>If you will think it worth while, pray refer to my description of <name key="Zannichellia%20Preissii">Zannichellia Preissii</name>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M had sent Hooker a MS description of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Zannichellia</seg> (not found), see M to W. Hooker, 6 April 1857 (in this edition as 57-04-06a).</p>
               </note> Sonder, who wrote the description for Lehmann,<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Lehmann (1844-7), vol 2, p. 3, in Sonder's treatment of Typhaceae.</p>
               </note> had no male flowers; I found &amp; examined them &amp; they showed <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">6-celled</hi>
               </seg> anthers invariably! It grows chiefly in brackish water on various localities <note type="frame"/>from Spencers Gulf to Gipps Land. I fear that it is not to be passed as Z. palustris.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Amphibolis">Amphibolis</name> is an excellent genus of which I have sent in 1853 a full designation of [femal] flowers and the remarkably large fruit.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">The text inside the marginal sketch is</seg> Fruit of <name key="Amphibolis">Amphibolis</name> Zosterifolia.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>58-10-15_image01.jpg</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Zostera%20uninervis">Zostera uninervis</name> Vahl grows also in Tasmania &amp; is [wi]dely distinct in the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">structure</hi>
               </seg> of fruit from Z. marina —. It accords fully with the British plant (Z. nana Roth). — <name key="Drymophila">Drymophila</name> grows in Victoria also. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0.0098in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Juncus%20capillaceus">Juncus capillaceus</name> can be traced into J. prismatocarpus. I fear the Tasmanian Junci have to be reduced. Luzula Oldfieldii I cannot help regarding as L. campestris <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">var</hi>
               </seg>
               <name key="Aphelia%20Gunnii">Aphelia Gunnii</name> = A. gracilis Sond in Linnaea 1856 p. 227.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Sonder (1856a).</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Desvauxia">Desvauxia</name> or <name key="Centrolepis%20glabra">Centrolepis glabra</name> is acknowledged by Sonder as <name key="Desvauxia">Desvauxia</name>.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Of Juncella I have a manuscript description, but I did not like to anticipate any work of the Tasmanian Flora — I will gladly adopt the name <name key="Trithuria">Trithuria</name>, because I have not been striving for personal glory but only for the truth, altho' on the other hand I think that if a humble disciple in our science as I am has sacrificed <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all his time &amp; means and the energy of not returning youth</hi>
               </seg> to the one object alone, promoting Australian botany — some little triumph may be granted for the discoveries, which arose under so many difficulties, sacrifice of health &amp; means and enormous labours caused by scantiness of books and collections</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Trithuria">Trithuria</name> is however also most closely indeed as I said in my transmitted msc. strikingly resembling <name key="Juncus%20capitatus">Juncus capitatus</name> Weigel! It is certainly not always submersed but grows like J. capitatus on wet places &amp; forms beautiful red carpets or caespites like that plant when inundated, altho with receding water the plant is green! I have given the name Juncella as early as 1848 and distributed it th[us] to the herbariums of St. Petersburg, Moscow, Vienne, [Berl]in, Paris &amp;c. The suborder which it forms combines as you very justly likewise pointed out <name key="Eriocauleae">Eriocauleae</name> and <name key="Desvauxieae">Desvauxieae</name>. Stuart sent it as an <name key="Eriocaulon">Eriocaulon</name> and I weighed the affinity fully when naming it. When I called it Tasmanica,<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Juncella tasmanica</seg> (B54.10.01).</p>
               </note> I had not visited Australia Felix, where I found the plant only 1853, but having distributed the plant so extensively (through Sonder) I did not like to change the specific name. But would under these views also not the name <name key="Dianella%20Tasmanica">Dianella Tasmanica</name> fall to the ground?</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have sent with the pharm Journal (containing some remarks on the affinity of <name key="Goodeniaceae">Goodeniaceae</name> a specimen of <name key="Goodenia%20amplexans">Goodenia amplexans</name> trans. ph. Inst. 1857 p. 70<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B57.09.04.</p>
               </note> This very rare plant, known to me only from near St. Vincents Gulf occurs in Stuarts private herbarium from the Nile Rivulet Tasmania He thought it to be G. barbata and either did not send on this supposition the plant or it was contained in the box, lost in the wreck of the "Henry" about 10 years ago.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See C. Stuart to M, 8 January 1849.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My garden report is just in print with a new catalogue &amp; combined with my fourth report as Gov. Botanist,<note xml:id="ftn14" type="footnote" n="14">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B58.11.02.</p>
               </note> but I fear I cannot send it before next mail.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Having been so overburdened with work and in consequence suffered from illness, I have been unable yet, to attend to the excellent Ch. Darwins request to experiment on the fecundation of <name key="Goodeniaceae">Goodeniaceae</name>. I have however scarcely as many species at hand for experiment, as the British Gardens, but will never the less at an early period attend to it.<note xml:id="ftn15" type="footnote" n="15">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">No evidence of a response by M to Darwin has been found. See Lucas (2010).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I ask one kind favor from your generosity, my dear Dr Hooker, to leave describing the Chatham Island Plants to me, as I am working on them already &amp; shall do justice to them with your excellent fl. antarc[.] &amp; N. Zeeland.<note xml:id="ftn16" type="footnote" n="16">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1844-7), J. Hooker (1853-5).</p>
               </note> — For bot Mag. I will send by next mail of the extraordinar <name key="Anchusa%20Chathamica">Anchusa Chathamica</name> a coloured drawing &amp; by one of the next clippers a big root. It has the leaves almost of a <name key="Funkia">Funkia</name>! <note xml:id="ftn17" type="footnote" n="17">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Almost certainly <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Myosotidium nobile</seg>: see B64.10.02, pp. 32-34.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>— I feel greatly indebted to Mr Bentham and Mr Blacks<note xml:id="ftn18" type="footnote" n="18">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Alan Black.</p>
               </note> editing the <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>e &amp; Eucalypti, and feel much honored to see the dissertations having been appreciated by the L.S.<note xml:id="ftn19" type="footnote" n="19">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B58.11.01, B59.12.01.</p>
               </note> — rest assured, I shall send them many pamphlets &amp; specimens henceforth like to Kew, but I have been absorbed in bringing the bot &amp; zool. Garden into more creditable working order &amp; could therefore not collect many specimens <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">of value</hi>
               </seg> to Kew from remote localities. I think you have all my good plants, except those from Lake Torrens, of which I gave all the duplicates to Sonder in 1852. Many many hours I could have saved in the examination of the plants for the Garden Catalogue, had I only had a copy of Bot. Mag. &amp; Bot. Regist.! — I think I ought to address in future Baillière.<note xml:id="ftn20" type="footnote" n="20">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Hippolyte Baillière.</p>
               </note> I am told he is so much more expeditious in carrying orders out than Pamplin.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The comparison of the Flora of India and North Australia becomes every day more interesting. I hear that Mr Bentham has undertaken the giants task to write an Australian Flora.<note xml:id="ftn21" type="footnote" n="21">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See G. Bentham to M, 23 August 1858.</p>
               </note> I wished I could help him! A more worthy successor to the completion the prodromus flor. Nov. Holl.<note xml:id="ftn22" type="footnote" n="22">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">R. Brown (1810).</p>
               </note> could not have been found, and a more honorable either. I could furnish a great deal of notes on the ranges of the species, if Mr Bentham would let me know when and how he intends to publish</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With my sincerest regards for your father &amp; yourself, I remain</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">your grateful Ferd. Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">never</hi>
               </seg> received the 1 &amp; 2 fasc. of flora Tasmanica you kindfully sent, nor any letter, which would put me on the lookout.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am most grateful to the Linnéans for printing my report,<note xml:id="ftn23" type="footnote" n="23">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B58.05.01.</p>
               </note> and by circulating the spare copies I can inspire some more men with ardor for botany.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Any further identifications from Mr Blacks will be very acceptable indeed. I intend to reward him now soon by naming a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">good</hi>
               </seg> plant after him.<note xml:id="ftn24" type="footnote" n="24">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See J. Hooker to M, 22 June 1858 for a comment on Black's role. M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Milletia blackii</seg> for Alan Black (B61.02.02).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
